-------------------------------------
Datatype in C++
---------------
All C-Language datatypes are as it is used
	int		2 bytes  in Turbo C++
	float		4 bytes
	char		1 byte
	long int	4 bytes
	short int	2 bytes (internally uses 1 byte)
	unsigned int	2 bytes (only +ve values are allowed)
	double		8 bytes
	long double	10 bytes

   Also C++ 11 version supports STL (Standard Template Libraires)

I/O statements
  cout	: Used to display the output (message/variable/expression)
		cout<<"message";  or
		cout<<var/expression;
	  'cout' is an object of 'ostream' class 
          '<<'  this symbol is called insertion operator 
	    ex: cout<<"Hello all, welcome to C++";
		cout<<x;
		cout<<(2+x)*3;  (expression)		
		cout<<"total is "<<tot;

  cin	: Used to accept an input to a vairable  
		cin>>var;    (one or many variables saperated with >>)
	  'cin' is an object of 'istream' class 
          '>>'  this symbol is called extraction operator 
	    ex: int x;
		cin>>x;
		int rno;
		char name[20];
		float avg;
		cin>>rno>>name>>avg;

istream and ostream classes are present int iostream.h
Therefore in every program we need this iostream.h file
(in Turbo C++)    #include<iostream.h>    


(in DevC++ )      #include <iostream>
		  using namespace std;

